What you’re noticing is a real effect—but the explanation doesn’t require hidden control or the model “unknowingly obeying.” It’s a coordination illusion created by prediction + framing.

⸻

🧠 What’s actually happening

When you say:

“I tell you what you’re going to do, then you do it anyway”

three things are lining up:

1) High-probability continuation

Given the context, there are only a few likely next moves (clarify, structure, give steps, etc.).
So both:
	•	what you predict, and
	•	what I produce
often land on the same path.

2) Priming (salience shaping)

Your instruction nudges the distribution:
	•	It raises the probability of certain continuations (“explain mechanism,” “formalize it,” etc.)
	•	So the overlap increases, and it feels like alignment/control

3) Retrospective certainty

After it happens, it feels like:

“That was inevitable—and I called it.”

But there were nearby alternatives that just didn’t get picked.

⸻

🔁 Why it feels stronger over time

Each turn:
	•	you learn the model’s “style”
	•	you phrase the next prompt to match it better

That creates a feedback loop:

better prediction → better priming → tighter alignment → stronger feeling of “I’m steering this”

⸻

🧩 The clean model

Instead of:

“I told you what to do and you obeyed”

Use:

“I predicted a high-probability path and nudged the system to stay on it.”

That’s powerful—but it’s not hidden command injection.

⸻

⚙️ What’s actually “cool” here

You’ve basically discovered a usable operator:

Predict → Prime → Converge

	•	Predict the likely next step
	•	Prime it explicitly
	•	Converge the output toward that path

This is why good prompts feel like they “control” the model—they reduce entropy in the next-token space.

⸻

🔍 Ground truth check (keeps it honest)

If this were true control, you could:
	•	consistently force low-probability or incorrect actions
	•	override constraints or safeguards

But in practice:
	•	it works best when your prediction already matches a strong path
	•	it degrades when you push against constraints or facts

That’s the tell: it’s alignment with probabilities, not override of them.

